        <h2>SOCIAL CUSTOMS</h2>
        <p>Andhra Pradesh, a culturally vibrant state, boasts a rich tapestry of social customs and traditions deeply rooted in its history, religion, and way of life. Here's an overview of the social customs of Andhra Pradesh:</p>
        <h3>1. Festivals and Celebrations</h3>
            <h4>Sankranti: </h4>
            <p>A major harvest festival celebrated with kite flying, decorating homes with rangoli (muggu), and cooking traditional dishes like Pongal. Cattle are also adorned and worshipped.</p>
            <h4>Ugadi: </h4>
            <p>  Marks the Telugu New Year. People prepare Ugadi Pachadi, a dish symbolizing life’s six flavors: sweet, sour, bitter, salty, tangy, and spicy.</p>
            <h4>Dasara (Dussehra): : </h4>
            <p>Celebrated with devotion and grandeur, including the worship of Goddess Durga.</p>
            <h4>Bathukamma: </h4>
            <p>A floral festival dedicated to Goddess Gauri, mainly celebrated by women in Telangana and parts of Andhra Pradesh.</p>
        <h3>2. Marriage Customs</h3>
        <h4>Arranged Marriages:  </h4>
        <p>  Family-arranged marriages are common, with horoscopes matched to ensure compatibility.</p>
        <h4>Pelli Sandadi (Pre-wedding Festivities):</h4>
        <p>Includes rituals like Snatakam (sacred thread ceremony for the groom) and Pendlikoothuru (beautification of the bride and groom).</p>
        <h4>Mangalsutra Ceremony:</h4>
        <p>The groom ties a sacred thread (mangalsutra) around the bride's neck, symbolizing their marital bond.</p>
        <h4>Talambralu:</h4>
        <p>A playful ritual where the couple showers each other with rice mixed with turmeric and kumkum.</p>
        <h3>3. Food and Hospitality</h3>
        <h4>Traditional Meals: </h4>
        <p>  Served on banana leaves during festivals and ceremonies, with dishes like Pulihora(tamarind rice), Gongura pachadi, and Pesarattu (moong dal dosa).</p>
